{"id":14881052,"mediaExerciseId":"387d9a43-c419-4df5-94f5-61ad7553dcbf","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":612313,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":233,"solutions":[{"id":5989834,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this task, **we have to calculate the bond's price. It is better if we use Spreadsheets to get the exact result.**","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"If you calculate it by hand, use the following formula:\n\n$$\\text{Price}=\\dfrac{\\text{C}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)}+\\dfrac{\\text{C}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{2}}+...+\\dfrac{\\text{C}+\\text{P}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{n}}$$\n\nC-coupon of the bond \n\nYTM-yield to maturity\n\nP-par value\n\nn-time","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"More specifically, **yield to maturity** is what an investor will earn if he holds the bond until the maturity date when the issuer pays back all the promised interest payments and the amount of the debt written in the contract (principal). In our case, it is 4.7 percent. We can say that this is a nominal interest rate at the annual level.\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/ad09b9f162d6f500108547991feaab41/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/ad09b9f162d6f500108547991feaab41/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"It is not the same as the **coupon rate**. Coupon rates are determined by the entity that issues a bond. In our case, it is 3.8 percent. The coupon value will be the same for every future payment. So it is a fixed amount.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Coupon value}&=\\text{par value}\\times\\text{coupon rate}\\\\\n\\\\\n&=\\$1,000\\times3.8\\%\\\\\n\\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$38}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nThe value of the coupon is \\$38. This amount is fixed for every year.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":291,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/077878ad51f1bc68dcfed58153257bbf/lateximg_large.png","width":845},"regular":{"height":147,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/077878ad51f1bc68dcfed58153257bbf/lateximg.png","width":423}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first insert the data from the exercise in the previous formula.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Price}&=\\dfrac{\\$38}{1+4.7\\%}+\\dfrac{\\$38}{\\left(1+4.7\\%\\right)^2}+...+\\dfrac{\\$38+\\$1,000}{\\left(1+4.7\\%\\right)^{23}}\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\$36.294+\\$34.665+...+\\$360,930\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\boxed{\\$875.0498}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n**The price of the bond is \\$875.05.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":176,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/41712cdb5728204c8d55100892fdcf63/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":89,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/06/cb5563d4298eb7f08b2ec0db38b0b782/41712cdb5728204c8d55100892fdcf63/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"a4b8d461-f818-482b-8071-18086ec09602","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ro